I'm trying to move a CSV from local storage to S3. My company uses temporary security tokens, so that the combination of AWS access key and secret key is not enough to authenticate with AWS/boto. Therefore, I'm trying to pass the S3 connection to odo via the `s3` parameter as supported in the [S3 __init__ method](https://github.com/blaze/odo/blob/master/odo/backends/aws.py#L69). That works fine to initialize the S3 connection, however, the `s3` keyword then collides with the `s3` named argument in the [append_text_to_s3 function](https://github.com/blaze/odo/blob/master/odo/backends/aws.py#L262). This results in a TypeError as shown below:

```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "test_s3.py", line 35, in test_odo
    odo.odo(os.path.realpath(self.local_path), 's3://abc123/mycsv.csv', s3=self.s3)
  File "/Users/abc123/PycharmProjects/S3_Test/venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/odo/odo.py", line 91, in odo
    return into(target, source, **kwargs)
  File "/Users/abc123/PycharmProjects/S3_Test/venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/multipledispatch/dispatcher.py", line 164, in __call__
    return func(*args, **kwargs)
  File "/Users/abc123/PycharmProjects/S3_Test/venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/odo/into.py", line 43, in wrapped
    return f(*args, **kwargs)
  File "/Users/abc123/PycharmProjects/S3_Test/venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/odo/into.py", line 149, in into_string_string
    return into(a, resource(b, **kwargs), **kwargs)
  File "/Users/abc123/PycharmProjects/S3_Test/venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/multipledispatch/dispatcher.py", line 164, in __call__
    return func(*args, **kwargs)
  File "/Users/abc123/PycharmProjects/S3_Test/venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/odo/into.py", line 43, in wrapped
    return f(*args, **kwargs)
  File "/Users/abc123/PycharmProjects/S3_Test/venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/odo/into.py", line 143, in into_string
    return into(a, b, dshape=dshape, **kwargs)
  File "/Users/abc123/PycharmProjects/S3_Test/venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/multipledispatch/dispatcher.py", line 164, in __call__
    return func(*args, **kwargs)
  File "/Users/abc123/PycharmProjects/S3_Test/venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/odo/into.py", line 43, in wrapped
    return f(*args, **kwargs)
  File "/Users/abc123/PycharmProjects/S3_Test/venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/odo/into.py", line 131, in into_object
    return append(target, source, dshape=dshape, **kwargs)
  File "/Users/abc123/PycharmProjects/S3_Test/venv/lib/python2.7/site-packages/multipledispatch/dispatcher.py", line 164, in __call__
    return func(*args, **kwargs)
TypeError: append_text_to_s3() got multiple values for keyword argument 's3'
```

I think the `s3` argument in `append_text_to_s3` should be renamed to something less generic to avoid this collision. I can submit a PR to do this if there are no objections.

As a developer, I want to copy data to S3 such that the resulting objects are encrypted, so that I can use Odo with sensitive data.

boto's set_contents_from_filename() can take an optional parameter encrypt=True, so there needs to be a way to pass that through the call chain such as append_text_to_s3().

Acceptance criteria:
Save data to S3 in a bucket such that the resulting object is encrypted with AES-256. One way to test this is that a bucket with the following policy, will not allow unencrypted puts:

```
{
   "Version":"2012-10-17",
   "Id":"PutObjPolicy",
   "Statement":[{
         "Sid":"DenyUnEncryptedObjectUploads",
         "Effect":"Deny",
         "Principal":"*",
         "Action":"s3:PutObject",
         "Resource":"arn:aws:s3:::mybucket/*",
         "Condition":{
            "StringNotEquals":{
               "s3:x-amz-server-side-encryption":"AES256"
            }
         }
      }
   ]
}
```
